'''Carrot and stick''' is a term usually used to refer to the act of rewarding good [[behaviour]] while threatening to punish bad behaviour.

An alternative definition comes from the visual image of a [[donkey]], forever walking towards the [[carrot]] suspended from a stick, just out of reach of his mouth. In this context, the stick is not used as a [[punishment]], but as a device to postpone fulfilment and encourage a reaction - in this case, forward movement. In [[copywriting]], for example, a carrot on the stick would be the 'teaser' explaning just enough of a topic to interest the reader and bring a response to the offer in the promotion. In copywriting the teasers are often never fulfilled because the writer has extracted the items from previously published material. It is not known if the donkey is usually given the carrot at the end of his travels. --[[User:Hobday|Hobday]] 16:24, 28 March 2006 (UTC)

